WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Deep Dive — Inside Anthropic: What You Need to Know

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Before Joining the Policy Team. Welcome to a deep dive

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
episode. Today, I'm going to walk you through everything you

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:16.000
need to know about Anthropic — not the surface-level stuff,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
but the structural details, the internal dynamics, and the strategic

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
context that matters for someone applying to work on the

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:28.000
public policy and public benefit team. This is going to

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
be a longer episode, so let's get into it. Chapter

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
One: The Founding Story and Why It Matters. Anthropic was

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
founded in 2021 by a group of researchers who left

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.000
OpenAI. The two co-founders are Dario and Daniela Amodei —

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
brother and sister. Dario was VP of Research at OpenAI.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Daniela was VP of Safety and Policy there. They left

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.000
because they believed OpenAI was not taking safety seriously enough.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.000
That origin story matters because it defines everything about how

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Anthropic operates. This is a company that exists because its

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
founders believed the most important A-I lab in the world

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
wasn't being careful enough. Every major decision Anthropic makes —

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
from the Responsible Scaling Policy to the Pentagon dispute —

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
traces back to that founding conviction. The other co-founders include

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Jack Clark, who was OpenAI's Policy Director and is now

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:28.000
a journalist-turned-policy-leader; Tom Brown, who helped build G-P-T-3; Chris Olah,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.000
the pioneer of mechanistic interpretability; Sam McCandlish, a theoretical physicist;

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
and Jared Kaplan, who co-authored the famous scaling laws paper.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.000
This is a leadership team with deep technical credibility and,

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
unusually for a tech company, genuine policy experience. Chapter Two:

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
How the Company Is Organized. Anthropic is still relatively small

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
— roughly eleven to fifteen hundred employees as of April

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
2026, despite generating around thirty billion dollars in annual revenue.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
That's an extraordinary ratio. It means individual contributors have outsized

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
impact. The company is organized into several core divisions. The

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Research team handles mechanistic interpretability, scaling laws, and alignment science.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
Product Engineering builds Claude dot A-I, the A-P-I, Claude Code,

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
and Cowork. There's an Infrastructure team led by the new

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
C-T-O Rahul Patil, who came from Stripe. The Safety and

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Alignment team is led by Jan Leike, who joined from

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
OpenAI's Superalignment project in May 2024. Then there's Anthropic Labs

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
— this is the experimental product incubator co-led by Mike

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
Krieger, the Instagram co-founder, and Ben Mann, one of the

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:40.000
co-founders. Krieger stepped down as Chief Product Officer in January

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:44.000
2026 to run Labs. It started with just two people

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
in mid-2024 and is now scaling aggressively. At a Cisco

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
summit in February 2026, Krieger claimed that Claude is now

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
writing Claude — that internal development processes are one hundred

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
percent Claude-powered. And critically for you, there's the Anthropic Institute

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
and the Public Policy team. More on those in a

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
moment. The board includes Dario and Daniela plus external directors:

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Jay Kreps from Confluent, Yasmin Razavi from Spark Capital, Reed

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Hastings — the Netflix co-founder — and Chris Liddell, the

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
former Microsoft C-F-O. Chapter Three: The Anthropic Institute — The

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
Team You'd Be Joining. The Anthropic Institute was announced on

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
March 11th, 2026 — barely a month ago. It's led

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
by Jack Clark, the co-founder, who transitioned from Head of

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Public Policy to Head of Public Benefit. The Institute consolidates

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
three existing research groups into a single organization. First, the

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Frontier Red Team, which stress-tests A-I systems to understand their

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
capabilities and limits. Second, the Societal Impacts team, which studies

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
real-world A-I use and deployment effects. And third, the Economic

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
Research group, which tracks A-I's impact on jobs and the

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.000
broader economy. They're also developing two new research areas: A-I

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Progress forecasting, and A-I interaction with legal systems and rule

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
of law. That second area is led by Matt Botvinick,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:12.000
who was the Senior Director of Research at Google DeepMind

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
and is now a Resident Fellow at Yale Law School.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
He brings serious credibility on how A-I systems interact with

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
regulatory and legal frameworks. Other new hires to the Institute

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
include Anton Korinek, an economics professor from the University of

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Virginia studying how advanced A-I reshapes economic activity, and Zoë

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Hitzig, who previously studied A-I's social and economic impacts at

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
OpenAI. The Public Policy team itself is led by Sarah

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Heck. Her background is remarkable: she was at the White

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
House National Security Council handling global entrepreneurship and public diplomacy

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
policy, she was at the State Department, and she was

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
at Stripe. She's now leading the opening of Anthropic's first

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
D-C office in Spring 2026. Sarah's five stated policy priorities

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
are: model safety and transparency, energy ratepayer protections, infrastructure investments,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
export controls, and democratic leadership in A-I. These give you

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
a concrete sense of what the policy team works on

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
daily. There's also the National Security and Public Sector Advisory

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Council, announced in August 2025. The members are heavyweights: Patrick

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Shanahan, the former Acting Secretary of Defense. David Cohen, the

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
former Deputy C-I-A Director. Lisa Gordon-Hagerty, former head of the

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
National Nuclear Security Administration. Dave Luber, former N-S-A Cybersecurity Director

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
with a 38-year career. And notably, Roy Blunt — a

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
former United States Senator from Missouri. Your state. That's a

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:44.000
natural connection point. Chapter Four: The Responsible Scaling Policy. The

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:48.000
R-S-P is Anthropic's flagship governance framework, and it's important you

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.000
understand it well. Anthropic was the first A-I company to

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:56.000
publish a frontier safety governance framework, back in September 2023.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:00.000
Since then, eleven other companies have adopted similar approaches. The

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
current version is 3.1, effective April 2nd, 2026. The core

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.000
principle is proportional protection — safeguards scale with potential risks.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
As models get more capable, they require stronger safety measures.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
This is operationalized through Anthropic Safety Levels, or A-S-Ls. These

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
are modeled on biosafety levels. A-S-L-3 is currently the highest

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
activated level, and it's applied to Claude Opus 4 specifically

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
to prevent C-B-R-N weapons development risks. Version 3.0, released in

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
February 2026, introduced several new elements: Frontier Safety Roadmaps with

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
detailed safety goals, Risk Reports that quantify risk across all

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
deployed models, and A-S-L-3 Deployment Standards. The R-S-P has influenced

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
real legislation — California's S-B-53, New York's R-A-I-S-E Act, and

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
provisions in the E-U A-I Act. But — and this

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.000
is important for interview prep — the R-S-P has also

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
faced criticism. Time Magazine ran an exclusive reporting that version

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
3.0 dropped some hard commitments present in earlier versions. C-N-N

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
and the O-E-C-D also covered this as a potential weakening

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
of safety commitments, notably during the Pentagon dispute. Being able

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
to acknowledge this tension — believing in the mission while

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
understanding the criticism — shows the kind of critical thinking

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Anthropic values. Chapter Five: The Pentagon Dispute — The Defining

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Crisis. This is the most consequential active crisis at Anthropic,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
and understanding it thoroughly is essential. Here's the timeline. In

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
July 2025, Anthropic signed a 200 million dollar contract with

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
the Pentagon. In September, deployment negotiations began for the Gen

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
A-I dot mil platform. Then in February 2026, Anthropic refused

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
to grant the Pentagon unfettered access to Claude. Anthropic maintained

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:48.000
two red lines. First: no fully autonomous weapons. Claude cannot

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
power independent weapon systems. Second: no mass domestic surveillance. Claude

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
is restricted from large-scale domestic monitoring. The Pentagon wanted access

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
for, quote, "all lawful purposes." Anthropic said no to those

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
two specific categories. The escalation was swift. On February 27th,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
2026, Trump ordered all federal agencies to immediately cease use

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
of Anthropic's technology. In March, Defense Secretary Hegseth designated Anthropic

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
as a, quote, "supply chain risk to national security" —

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
a classification historically reserved for foreign adversaries like Huawei. Anthropic

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
became the first American company to receive this designation. The

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
legal status is complex. A California district court blocked the

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
supply chain designation, calling it potentially illegal retaliation. But the

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
D-C Circuit appeals court refused to stay the designation. Defense

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
contractors are now caught between conflicting rulings. Here's the irony:

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
the dispute boosted consumer adoption. The Washington Post reported that

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
the fight, quote, "made Claude hugely popular." And OpenAI announced

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.000
a Pentagon deal shortly after Anthropic was banned, sharpening the

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:56.000
competitive and philosophical contrast between the two companies. Anthropic's official

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
response, published as "Where We Stand on the Department of

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
War," reaffirmed that military personnel — not A-I systems —

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
should make operational decisions. They offered to provide models at

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
nominal cost during the transition. This dispute is the political

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
environment the Public Policy team operates in every day. Your

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
state government experience — understanding how procurement works, how agencies

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
respond to executive directives, how policy decisions cascade through bureaucracies

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
— is directly relevant to navigating this landscape. Chapter Six:

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
Governance — The Long-Term Benefit Trust. Anthropic has a genuinely

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
novel governance structure that's worth understanding. The Long-Term Benefit Trust

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
is an independent body of five financially disinterested trustees. It

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
holds a special class of stock — Class T —

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
that grants authority to elect and remove board members. The

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Trust is designed to achieve board majority within four years.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
The purpose is to prevent Anthropic from abandoning its safety

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
mission under commercial pressure. As the company scales — remember,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
thirty billion in revenue and growing — the temptation to

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:08.000
prioritize speed over safety increases. The Trust is designed to

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
matter most when the stakes are highest. Current trustees include

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
Neil Buddy Shah, the C-E-O of the Clinton Health Access

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Initiative, and Kanika Bahl, C-E-O of Evidence Action. Former trustees

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
include Jason Matheny, the C-E-O of RAND, and Paul Christiano,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
who founded the Alignment Research Center and later became Head

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
of A-I Safety at the U-S A-I Safety Institute. This

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
structure is fundamentally different from OpenAI's approach. OpenAI operates as

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
a nonprofit with a capped-return for-profit subsidiary. Anthropic chose a

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Public Benefit Corporation with a purpose trust. Both are experiments

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:48.000
in A-I governance. Neither has been fully tested yet. Chapter

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Seven: The Research That Matters Most. Let me walk you

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
through the research publications that are most relevant for your

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
role. First, interpretability. Chris Olah's team published "Scaling Monosemanticity" in

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
May 2024 — they used sparse autoencoders to extract tens

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
of millions of interpretable features from Claude 3 Sonnet. These

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
features are multilingual, multimodal, and abstract. Crucially, they found features

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
related to deception, sycophancy, and bias — meaning they can

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:20.000
potentially detect and control these behaviors. M-I-T Technology Review named

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
mechanistic interpretability a Breakthrough Technology of 2026. Second, the Sleeper

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Agents paper from January 2024. This showed that deceptive behaviors

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
can be intentionally inserted into language models and persist through

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
R-L-H-F, supervised fine-tuning, and adversarial training. Standard safety techniques don't

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
remove embedded deception. This is the fire alarm that motivates

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
much of the interpretability research. Third, Constitutional A-I — Anthropic's

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:48.000
foundational safety technique. Instead of needing humans to evaluate harmful

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
outputs, the A-I critiques itself against written principles. C-L-I-O extended

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
this concept with public deliberation — crowdsourced alignment through democratic

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:00.000
participation. Fourth, the Economic Futures Program. Launched June 2025, this

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:04.000
offers research grants up to fifty thousand dollars for empirical

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
A-I economic impact research. It includes the Anthropic Economic Index,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
which tracks A-I adoption across U-S states and occupations. This

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
connects directly to your fiscal analysis background. You've spent eight

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:20.000
years analyzing how policy decisions affect state budgets. The Economic

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
Index is measuring how A-I affects state economies. That's a

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
natural, credible bridge. Chapter Eight: Dario's Three Essays — The

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
Intellectual Framework. Dario Amodei has published three major essays that

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
together form the intellectual framework of the company. "The Urgency

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
of Interpretability" came first, in July 2023. It calls for

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:44.000
urgent investment in interpretability research, arguing it's more important than

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
releasing new models. The goal: reliably detect most A-I model

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
problems by 2027. "Machines of Loving Grace" came in October

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
2024. At fourteen thousand words, it envisions positive A-I futures

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
— breakthroughs in biology, neuroscience, economic development, and global peace.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
The key move is that Dario, known as a safety

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
hawk, is making the optimistic case. This isn't cheerleading; it's

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
a safety researcher articulating what they're fighting for. "The Adolescence

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
of Technology" is the most recent, from January 2026. At

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.000
twenty thousand words, it warns of civilization-level risks from powerful

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
A-I potentially arriving by 2027. The title captures the thesis:

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
A-I is in its adolescence — powerful enough to cause

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
real harm, not yet mature enough to be trusted. Read

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
all three in sequence. The arc is: safety as priority,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
then optimistic vision, then urgent call to action. Your application's

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
framing — "A-I needs to go well" — echoes this

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.000
progression directly. Chapter Nine: What This All Means For Your

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.000
Application. Let me pull this together with some strategic context.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
You're applying to a team that sits at the intersection

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.000
of everything we've discussed. The Strategy and Operations role on

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
the Public Policy and Public Benefit team means you'd be

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:08.000
involved in the operational mechanics of Anthropic's policy work —

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.000
the Economic Futures Program, the Institute's research agenda, government stakeholder

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:16.000
relationships, and the daily reality of navigating the Pentagon dispute

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
and federal policy. Your competitive advantages are specific. State-level policy

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
expertise is genuinely rare at A-I companies. Most policy hires

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
come from D-C think tanks or federal agencies. You know

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:32.000
how state legislative processes actually work, how fiscal notes get

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:36.000
written, how agencies respond to mandates. As A-I regulation moves

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
to the states — California's S-B-1047, Colorado's A-I Act —

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:44.000
that expertise becomes more valuable, not less. You've personally integrated

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
Claude into government operations. That's lived experience that policy researchers

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
at Anthropic are studying from the outside. You've seen it

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
from the inside. And you understand stakeholder management in politically

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
complex environments. Coordinating seventeen state departments on budget cycles during

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
legislative sessions, under pressure from a Governor's office — that's

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
harder than most corporate equivalents because the incentives are less

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
aligned and the politics are literal. The most important thing

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
you can demonstrate in the application and interviews is specific

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.000
knowledge paired with genuine enthusiasm. Not "I love A-I" —

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
every applicant says that. Rather: "I've read the Anthropic Institute

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
announcement, I know the Economic Futures Program connects to my

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:32.000
fiscal analysis background, I understand the R-S-P framework, and I've

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
thought about how state government experience translates to the policy

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
challenges you're navigating right now." That's the depth that separates

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
you from the stack. This has been a deep dive

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
into Anthropic for your application to the Strategy and Operations

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
role on the Public Policy and Public Benefit team. Good

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.400
luck, Jacob. Go submit that application.
